This is a tray that you can bolt to the underside of the FPV250 found at hobbyking. In my case this allowed me to mount a 4xESC to the bottom of the airframe, and then mount the battery to the tray.  
The feet line up with holes in the frame. I used 3mm cap head screws to secure it in place. I've crashed my quad a few times already and the tray is holding up fine.

I recommend printing these at 100% infill if you can. That gives it the structural integrity to take hard landings and crashes without breaking. PLA or ABS should be fine, I have printed it in both materials. I'm flying the PLA version as I prefer the rigidity which seems better matched to the frame itself.  
After printing you will likely need to ream the holes in the feet out a bit. I used a 3mm tap on my PLA one. You could also most likely use a 2.5 mm drill bit. The trick is that the hole still needs to be tight so that the screws get a good bite on the plastic.

This is a bearing holder for the Hatchbox 1kg filament spools. The inner hole diameter is just over 16mm (to account for cooling/shrink) and may need to be adjusted based on your particular filament. You can also skip the actual bearing and just run a half inch dowel through the spool.
I added a customizable version, with nearly every parameter you could need. I also added a lip for the bearing to set in so that the tolerances don't need to be so tight to actually hold the bearing.

You can print this flat with no supports. The prongs will be stronger if you print the part vertically, but you'll either need to add supports or use software that adds them for you. I printed mine flat with no supports and just eased them into the spool so I could get them back out.  
Sketchup source file is included. I didn't clean up all the intermediate lines yet.
OpenSCAD source now included. 
The parameters should be self explanatory. If you don't want the lip for the bearing, just set the width to 0. If you include the lip, you'll most likely need supports unless your printer can handle the overhang (I recommend a mm or 2, I think many printers can handle the 1mm overhang without supports).

title: Injection Printing - Injection Molding with your 3D printer

description.text:
Using the differing melting properties of ABS and PLA, you can use the functions of your 3D printer to make rudimentary injection molded parts. For more information:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:83805 For even more information with complete instructions:
http://www.instructables.com/id/Use-Your-3D-Printer-As-An-Injection-Molder/

This is one of those "I wonder if it can be done" exercises you can do in about an hour.  This is only a proof-of-concept experiment that opens up the possibility of further development if anyone is interested.  
The part I made is a true molded piece having no deposited layers.  
The vent sprue I drilled in the front of the upper mold half didn't work as PLA was too thick to move through (you can see the tiny nub in the photos).  When the die was filled, the plastic simply began to pile up around the extruder head, outside the die,.  
The other issue I had was the extruder head was hot enough to deform the upper ABS die half.  This didn't effect the part, but it made removing it from the mold difficult.  The heat allowed the ABS mold material and the PLA part material to be mixed, making extraction impossible without wrecking the upper half of the mold.  
Here's how I made this:  
Print the stl file in ABS.  When the print is complete, break off the upper half (the one with the opening) and place it on top of the lower half, which should still be adhered to the build plate.  
Disengage the driver motors and move the PLA print head (or the same print head you used to built the die on a single extruder machine)  Load PLA material into the extruder and raise the plate until the extruder head couples with the hollow on the top of the die.  Turn the load function on.  The PLA will flow, filling the cavity.  When its full, the PLA will begin to squeeze out from around the extruder nozzle.  That's when you should shut the extruder off.  
Let the plastic cool completely before cracking the die open with a screw driver.  If all went well, the part will be sitting inside the die, looking like a pearl.  
Have fun, experiment and let us know if you make something really cool.

description.text:
Many people have at least one toilet in their home where the seat REFUSES to stay in the upright position!
Rather than adjusting the seat or moving the Cistern - which would be the 'proper' fix - you can spend twice as long making this 'engineered' solution and save an afternoon of unwelcome DIY.
Just clip the holder on to the top lip of the cistern with the lid removed and position such that the seat is caught by one of the barbs.

title: PolyBot Servo Mount with Screw Hole

description.text:
In the post mortem of my wife's PolyBot assembly, one of the things she wanted was a hole to put a screw through the servo mount to hold it to the platform.
This thing is the exact same as the previous version, with the addition of an M3 sized mounting hole, and an indent for the matchich hex nut on the 'bottom' side of it.
I considered having more holes for more holding goodness, but I'm still sticking with the minimal fasteners design principle.

1) Print a few of these out
2) Fit standard sized servos into them
3) Drill an M3 sized hole in the shelf
4) Mount them on a 1/4" shelf
5) Put a M3 sized screw through the hole
6) Put an M3 sized hex nut under the bottom, and tighten. You might want to put a washer on the topside.
7) Rejoice! With the OpenScad file, you can easily change anything from the shelf thickness, to the hole size, so you're not stuck with the M3 sizing.

description.text:
This Thing is a two-part filament spool holder for the Bits-From-Bytes (BFB, now part of 3D Systems) 3DTouch printer. The spool holders which come with the original printer are for filament spools with very large holes (> 3 inches), which are hard to find these days. To keep the printer running smoothly, replace the OEM spool holders with these, which support filament spools with holes down to 3 cm.  
Designed in partnership with Bing GAN and the WOOF3D team at the University of Washington.

Prints fine on a FlashForge Creator, no support. Print the top insert upside down (for better bed adhesion), possibly with a raft. I used 3 shells, 10% infill, and the base takes a little over two hours.  
Once printed, insert the bearing from the original assembly (or a replacement bearing - 7/8 in OD, 1/4 in thick) into the Bottom part. Squeeze the two fins on the Top together and insert into Bottom, twisting to snap locks into place. Insert the bolt from the top. Place the spacer (part of the original spool holder) on the protruding bolt out the bottom, and insert the assembly into the 3DTouch. Fasten on the bottom with the original nut.

So I use a 6' pole to get elevated shots. Problem is the mount is rigid and so the camera angle changes with the angle of the pole.  
Solution, a single axis free floating gimbal. I printed with 50% infill and 4 perimeters.  
The pivot point is made for a 8/32 bolt and nut (I use them all day and I don't have any metric). Either leave the nut loose (suggest a lock nut) or do what I did and glue the screws to the inside of the frame, it will not come apart this way unless you pull on the frame wall.

Have you ever wanted to watch your MakerBot print while you are away? Perhaps setup a live feed of your MakerBot? Or just want to add a webcam to your MakerBot? Then this will hopefully help you out. The MakerBot Webcam Attachment (It needs a better name) is a printable mount that attaches your webcam to a printable arm which connects to the frame of your MakerBot. By setting up a VNC server on the computer controlling your MakerBot and attaching the webcam, you will then be able to control and watch your MakerBot from any computer in the world with internet access! Also, you could setup a web sever on that computer and host a live stream of what is print on your MakerBot. Now the question is, Is this a MakerCam or do you have a WebBot?
If anyone has questions about setting up a web server or a VNC server, I'll do my best to answer them. This is sized for a Microsoft LifeCam HD-5000 [ http://www.microsoft.com/hardware/en-us/p/lifecam-hd-5000/7ND-00001 ], but can easily be modified for a different camera with the included SCAD file. The last image is a sample taken from the webcam. WARNING: As barrychuck brought out, running a MakerBot while unattended is very dangerous. I am not responsible for any damage or harm that occurs from use of this part. Use this at your own risk!

Print out the following parts:
1x "Webcam_Clamp.stl"
1x "MakerBot_Clamp.stl"
5x "Webcam_Clamp Arms.stl" Assemble the parts as shown in the 4th picture. You can use M3 bolts instead of #4-40. Insert your webcam and attach it to your MakerBot's frame.

title: M38 scope for E11 Stormtrooper Blaster

description.text: This is the scope from ProCoPrint3D's E11 blaster, scaled up a shade for a 40 mm pipe build, then cleaned and sliced into pieces for easy supportless printing. It's for those of us who have dodgy 3D-printers.

I've not finished test printing this, so there may be bugs, even though NetFabb Basic says it's all right. I started constructing my own scope from blueprints some time before ProCoPrint3D released his extremely detailed blaster in parts. I liked his scope better than mine, as I couldn't quite get the curved edges to look the way I wanted. Since my 3D printer doesn't like printing overhang, and supports get messy, I just sliced up ProCoPrint3D's scope and decided to share it in here. I may just do that with more of the parts, as I'm building an E11 blaster based on a piece of 40 mm plastic pipe, and it's a lot quicker and easier to use parts that are already out there. There are three alternative cone shaped parts in the download section. Obviously, you only need one, but since I'd already designed most of my own scope, I uploaded one of the parts I felt happy with. I've added the little wedge with the number on it on the side in my own design. The one called "Scope 4.stl" is from ProCoPrint3D's scope. The one called "Scope 4 alternative 2.stl" is my design squashed roughly to the shape of ProCoPrint3D's. The one called "Scope 4 alternative 2.stl" is my original design based on blueprints I found online. I thought my scope looked slightly too long with that one, but as I haven't got any real M38 scope to compare it to, I don't really know which one is closest to the real thing. The parts should be roughly interchangeable, at least it looks that way in Sketchup. As I mentioned earlier, I haven't tested all the bits yet. The parts are numbered from front to back. Use the "Scope Assembly.stl" for reference if in doubt.

comments.text: Hi Yngel . . . I printed and test fit all pieces . . . I noticed that the two alternative scope pieces did not have the right footprint on the small diameter cone . . . the regular piece did fit correctly but the two alternatives were slightly smaller than middle block.  The scope I built and pic uploaded is with the regular scope cone piece (Scope_4  . . . without the #2).

https://github.com/syvwlch/Printable-Clock-Project/commit/d9a7dec80f6a474103868612170651c668f812d3 v4 - 2011 05 18
Modified to support the ratcheting drum designed by rustedrobot.

There are things that get re-used by various clocks and test jigs, but don't really merit inclusion in the library itself. I got a little tired of managing multiple clock scripts, and having to make sure the latest improvements made it into the various configurations.
So, all this common logic, for placing the gears, making them mesh and rotate, or laying them out to print, etc... that's all now contained in this clock builder script which calls MCAD for the gears and my clockwork library for the clockwork.
It, in turn is called by short scripts that contain only the parameter values for a particular clock, and any clock-specific code you might care to add (like a frame design, since I haven't come up with a good generic one yet).
Which means that if you want to play with clock configurations with as little as two or as many as nine wheels, with all, any or none of them bearing hands and/or concentric shafts, curled up as loose or as tight as you want, all you need to do is create a copy of a clock-script, and modify parameters to your heart's content. The core code and parameters are unchanged.

You will need a copy of MCAD/involute_gears, of my clockwork library, this clock builder script, and at least one clock script (e.g. the ones listed here as derivatives).
Open the clock script and hit F5 to compile. Save it under a different name, change the parameters (remove a gear, add a gear, add a hand, change the folding angle of the gear train, etc...) and hit F5 again to recompile.
The first clock script I will upload to Thingiverse will be the current version of the test jig, which incorporates rustedrobot's latest feedback from his experiments with the previous version.

description.text:
Maybe too soon for halloween but still it makes a good "scary" easy print :)  
It should look great in white color (duh)

The original thing was designed to fit into a socket, with nothing more than the socket structure itself holding it in place.  I wanted to create another type of holder, so I added a couple of 2mm dimples to the sphere.
This thing has 2mm dimples built into opposing sides of the sphere.  Given the appropriate holder, you can hold onto these spheres using protrusions, and not just the friction fit of the socket.
Depending on the socket you put it in, you might get the best of both worlds.  You could have a socket with protrusions in various fixed positions, which will snap into the dimples on this sphere.
At any rate, this derivative is just a tiny bit more functional than the last version.

1) Print a few of these
2) Slip them onto 5/16" rods
3) Snap them into the appropriate holder
4) Rejoice!
